stories: Musculoskeletal diseases and cognitive impairments in patients result in movement difficulties and negative impacts on their mental well-being. Clinical gait analysis, crucial for early diagnosis and treatment, has traditionally relied on costly optical motion capture systems. Recent advancements in computer vision and deep learning have made more accessible and affordable alternatives possible. This study presents a new spatial-temporal transformer network for estimating important gait parameters from RGB videos captured by a single-view camera. Empirical assessments on a public dataset of cerebral palsy patients demonstrate that the proposed framework outperforms current best practices and offers significant enhancements in predicting key gait parameters (such as walking speed, gait deviation index - GDI, and knee flexion angle at maximum extension) while requiring fewer parameters and eliminating the need for manual feature extraction.

Patients with musculoskeletal diseases and cognitive impairments often face movement difficulties and negative effects on their mental well-being. Traditional clinical gait analysis has relied on expensive optical motion capture systems, but recent advances in computer vision and deep learning have opened up more cost-effective options. A new spatial-temporal transformer network is introduced in this study for estimating important gait parameters from RGB videos captured by a single-view camera. Testing on a dataset of cerebral palsy patients shows that this framework outperforms current methods, offering improvements in predicting key gait parameters without the need for manual feature extraction.
